<div id="review_3120236193" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3120236193" />
    <a title="KLC" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18572396-klc"><img alt="KLC" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578430158p2/18572396.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3120236193?book_show_action=true">Jan 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="KLC" class="user" itemprop="url" name="KLC" href="/user/show/18572396-klc">KLC</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3120236193" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18363509138212765664">What can you say about a book like this? It’s hard to give it a star rating, but I didn’t want to leave this on my “Read” shelf without also leaving an explanation. I got it from the library because it had a pretty cover and I assumed it was some kind of epic story of heroism. It ended up being a bit different than I had originally thought ...<br/><br/>Some of the advice is laughable and the entire thing objectifies women - as one would expect from a centuries-old book - but some of it is refreshingly acc</span>
  <span id="freeText18363509138212765664" style="display:none">What can you say about a book like this? It’s hard to give it a star rating, but I didn’t want to leave this on my “Read” shelf without also leaving an explanation. I got it from the library because it had a pretty cover and I assumed it was some kind of epic story of heroism. It ended up being a bit different than I had originally thought ...<br /><br />Some of the advice is laughable and the entire thing objectifies women - as one would expect from a centuries-old book - but some of it is refreshingly accurate. There’s a heavy emphasis on foreplay for the woman and intimacy. It encourages men not to do the whole “wham, bam, thank you, ma’am” thing. In the words of the book: “... withdraw your member cautiously. Remain close to the woman … and you will not be like a fellow who mounts the woman after the fashion of a mule …” I kinda wish this book was more popular nowadays because a lot of modern men could learn a thing or two.<br /><br />It goes on to say that if the man “comes down softly on her right side, and if she has conceived, she will bear a male child, if it please God on high!” So, you know, if you stay by her side after doing the deed, you’ll definitely have a baby boy … Maybe. <br /><br />It also shares some positions to try, like the “fitting on of the sock,” “he-goat fashion,” “driving the peg home,” and “the one who stops in the house.” You can also learn to make love while balancing a lit lamp on your foot. <br /><br />Despite how ridiculous parts of this book are, I think it’s a good resource to learn more about that culture and not much else. I think 2020 will go down in my own personal history as the year with the most awkward first read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18363509138212765664" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


