<div id="review_2515185686" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2515185686" />
    <a title="Helen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7392549-helen"><img alt="Helen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1440070776p2/7392549.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2515185686?book_show_action=true">Sep 01, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Helen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Helen" href="/user/show/7392549-helen">Helen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title=" 9780600564232" href="/book/show/1780663.The_ILLUSTRATED_PERFUMED_GARDEN">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2515185686" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6940127740721450058">Nice hardback edition with illustrations. It’s an interesting read, not “accurate” to western/modern/feminist minds, in terms of sexual biology and responses, and it’s certainly not right in terms of the woman’s place in society but is of its time and location. <br/><br/>It’s post-Mohammedan circa early C16th, and is told in stories and instruction. On first read, it appears to be very negative towards woman but it actually gives women a lot of power, and credits them with wiles and but also an easily man</span>
  <span id="freeText6940127740721450058" style="display:none">Nice hardback edition with illustrations. It’s an interesting read, not “accurate” to western/modern/feminist minds, in terms of sexual biology and responses, and it’s certainly not right in terms of the woman’s place in society but is of its time and location. <br /><br />It’s post-Mohammedan circa early C16th, and is told in stories and instruction. On first read, it appears to be very negative towards woman but it actually gives women a lot of power, and credits them with wiles and but also an easily manipulated one track mind!! <br /><br />It’s plus points emphasise foreplay and consent (except one “position”) and equality of pleasure, unrealistic fantasy mutual pleasure, in some cases, with rather overinflated representation of male endowments and prowess. <br /><br />The Perfume Garden’s main forte is describing suitable positions and the focus on inciting desire, and waiting ‘till a woman is ready, and doing things to please the woman wherein lies ultimate pleasure for the man. The positions take some interpretation, and the pictures don’t readily translate to the text but overall the book is interesting... historically and sexually. Read in conduction with a modern version it would be fun for intimate play. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6940127740721450058" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


